disease description: Powdery mildew is a fungal disease caused by various species of fungi such as Erysiphe and Sphaerotheca. These plant diseases can affect both indoor and outdoor plants. Powdery Mildew can be identified as a white or gray powdery coating on the surfaces of stems, fruits, and leaves of the plant. Powdery mildew can halt photosynthesis and can weaken plant health.

Powdery mildew is a bacterial disease of cabbage and other crucifers caused by Xanthomonas campestris, leading to yellow, V-shaped lesions with black veins, and a fungal disease of grapes (Guignardia bidwellii or Phyllosticta ampelicida) that causes black spots and mummified fruit.
Leaf spot is a plant disease causing discolored lesions on leaves, triggered by fungal, bacterial, or viral pathogens, or environmental factors.
A a large genus of fungi that cause a common and destructive group of plant diseases called Cercospora leaf spot.

Rust is another plant disease caused by various species of fungi from the Puccinia genus. Plant disease identification for rust is orange, yellow, or reddish-brown pustules on the surface of leaves, fruits, and stems of the plant. These pustules burst and release powdery spores that spread through water and air. Infected plants may show signs of stunted growth, yellowing leaves, premature leaf drop, and an overall decline in plant health.

A a broad term for plant diseases where leaves develop necrotic (dead) areas, often appearing as yellow or brown spots, patches, or lesions that can expand and lead to browning, wilting, and death of foliage.

A destructive trunk disease of mature grapevines, caused by a complex of fungal pathogens that attack the wood tissue. It is a major threat to viticulture globally, causing significant reductions in yield and eventually leading to vine death.
It is one of the most destructive and lethal diseases affecting citrus crops worldwide.

A a plant disease caused by Xanthomonas bacteria that primarily affects the foliage, stems, and fruit of plants in the nightshade family, such as peppers and tomatoes. It thrives in warm, humid climates and is highly difficult to control once established.
A a physiological disorder, not a disease, caused by the plant's inability to move enough water to its leaves to replace moisture lost through transpiration.

They are common plant pests belonging to the arachnid family, not insects. They are a major threat to a wide range of plants, including vegetables, fruits, and houseplants, and thrive in hot, dry conditions.

A a plant virus, such as the Tobacco Mosaic Virus (TMV) and Cucumber Mosaic Virus (CMV), that causes a distinctive 'mosaic' pattern of mottled, discolored patches on leaves, often with light and dark green or yellow areas.

A DNA virus from the genus Begomovirus and the family Geminiviridae. TYLCV is one of the most serious diseases affecting tomato plants, especially in tropical and subtropical areas, where it often causes major crop losses.
